## v1.3.0 (2026-06-13)

Documents guard-test negative-path pattern, job-key vs context-name disambiguation,
destructive PUT mitigation, and requirements-deviation disclosure from ProjectHephaestus
issue #1315 NOGO review cycle.

- Added section F: Guard test with provable negative path — extracted `_unwired_jobs(wf,
  excluded)` pure helper; 3-test pattern (positive, negative with synthetic dummy-job,
  excluded-not-flagged). The negative-path test proves the helper can detect gaps, not
  just that the current workflow happens to pass.
- Added section G: Job key vs. context name disambiguation table — `needs:` uses YAML job
  keys; branch protection contexts use the job `name:` field. They diverge when `name:`
  contains slashes (e.g., `security/dependency-scan`). Practical rule: read actual context
  names from `gh api .../check-runs`, not from the YAML job key.
- Added section H: Destructive PUT mitigation pattern — GET-before-PUT snapshot, manual
  field merge, `enforce_admins: false` default, note that org-level rulesets are NOT
  affected by branch-level PUT. Preferred alternative: use PATCH on sub-resources.
- Added section I: Requirements deviation disclosure pattern — any deviation from the
  issue's literal text (dropping contexts, changing reviewer count, substituting API) must
  be called out explicitly in the plan or PR body with "Flagged for issue-author
  confirmation." Implicit deviations = NOGO.
- Added three new Failed Attempts rows: guard test without negative path, `enforce_admins:
  true` in PUT payload, requirements deviation left implicit.
- Updated description frontmatter with four new trigger scenarios (F–I).
- Updated Overview Objective and Verification fields.
- Updated Verified On table with NOGO review cycle entry.
